This repository contains two fundamental searching algorithms implemented in C++:

Linear Search: Linear Search is a simple searching algorithm that checks each element of the array one by one until the desired element is found or the list ends.
      
              ðŸ”¹How linear search works -

                    i. Start from the first element.
                    ii. Compare each element with the target value.
                    iii. If found, return the index.
                    iv. If not found after checking all elements, return "Not Found".

ðŸ”¹ Time Complexity
      - Best Case: O(1)
      - Worst Case: O(n)

ðŸ”¹ Suitable For
   - Small datasets
   - Unsorted arrays
2. Binary Search: Binary Search is an efficient searching algorithm that works only on sorted arrays. It repeatedly divides the search interval into halves.
ðŸ”¹ How binary search works -
      i. Find the middle element.
      ii. If the target equals the middle element â†’ Found.
      iii. If target is smaller â†’ Search left half.
      iv. If target is larger â†’ Search right half.
      v. Repeat until found or interval becomes empty.
ðŸ”¹ Time Complexity
     - Best Case: O(1)
     - Worst Case: O(log n)
ðŸ”¹ Suitable For
      - Large datasets
      - Sorted arrays
